        <title>War with Spain</title>
    </head>
    <body>
        <section class="segment-opener" data-uuid="8de78acb36734db8b8686fdc6f43957e">
            <article data-uuid="dbc327adffe24c978ff4359ee716c07d">
                <h4 data-uuid="f9b788c26a034d1ea085d494bd0f5c6f">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="baa01cf862b74c389b2d3abe72795f47">
                    In 1898 the United States went to war with Spain in the Spanish-American War.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="9b6cc70385c844eabf043ec46af012d7">War with Spain</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="c010ad32e9fb433aac255713ca811965"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <section class="graphic-organizer-prompt " data-uuid="e0ef7a5ee3844d38ac8974c2a0f6b3c7">
            <div class="go-prompt-bottom-bar" data-uuid="520d0e1924224d0ba750127731e6b322">
                <p data-uuid="16c58b30c896490d8123f6f5c1440412">As you read, use the graphic organizer to take notes on the arguments for and against U.S. imperialism in Latin America.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="a5b0499fbdd94fb9beee7639440adf69">You read earlier that newspaper publishers Joseph Pulitzer and William Randolph Hearst were in a fierce competition for readers. In the late 1890s their newspapers published stories from Cuba, where Cuban rebels were fighting for independence from Spain. To attract readers, Pulitzer and Hearst printed sensational, often exaggerated, news stories. This technique is called <b><dfn title="yellow journalism">yellow journalism</dfn></b>. Vivid stories about Spanish brutality in Cuba convinced many Americans that the U.S. military should support the Cuban rebels.<br />
        </p>
        <figure class="image-with-caption one-half right top-align" data-uuid="ed1eb3658c9b45caa47b503a073f0448">
            <img alt="This black-and-white photo of the front page of the newspaper “The World” is an example of yellow journalism. The title of the article is “Maine Explosion Caused by Bomb or Torpedo.” For more information, ask your teacher to describe this photo to you. " class="" data-uuid="271d6dd88f0e429e8b20eff680797eb1" src="../../img/module_23_lesson02/ms_snlese454149_637p.jpg" />
            <div class="figcaption" data-uuid="f12e45691aad4e0b8beb4e784c277d63">
                <p class="caption" data-uuid="d49884de7c714d308245848f25c4278f"><span>Newspapers such as this one used yellow journalism to&#160;</span><span>encourage Americans to seek war with Spain.</span><br />
                </p>
            </div>
        </figure>
        <p data-uuid="69bfce4f404549f1b4233a1d57bdd44b">Despite growing support for military action in Cuba, President Grover Cleveland was opposed to U.S. involvement. In 1896 William McKinley, a supporter of Cuban independence, was elected president. At first, he was against war, but American public opinion forced him to take action. Several events soon led to war.</p>
        <p data-uuid="ef5123eedec34841a3650879d0742d9c">In February 1898 Hearst’s newspaper published a letter written by the Spanish minister to the United States, Enrique Dupuy de L&#244;me. In it, de L&#244;me called McKinley “weak and a bidder for the admiration of the crowd.” Many Americans were outraged.</p>
        <p data-uuid="77cf8eff74e34e09ae0c32a906cada94"> In January 1898, even before de L&#244;me’s letter became public, the United States sent the battleship USS <i>Maine</i> to Havana Harbor. Riots had broken out in Havana, the Cuban capital. The <i>Maine</i>’s mission was to protect U.S. citizens and economic interests in Cuba from the violence. On February 15 the <i>Maine</i> exploded and sank, with a loss of 266 men. Although the cause of the explosion was unclear, the American press immediately blamed Spain. “Remember the <i>Maine</i>!” became a rallying cry for angry Americans.<br />
        </p>
        <section class="historical-source nobg" data-uuid="bdf7378e20764af6b689533b2da0bf9e">
            <article class="box gradient" data-uuid="f62219f4499d405b8e2ae3336dcc2ec4">
                <div class="header-element" data-uuid="c312100de8a442808c8bbff719fd78b1">
                    <h2 class="label" data-uuid="56adfd4eb3794217a027603ddc771614">Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="fcbb28d268264fbf8d3ba260256bc3ff">
                    <h2 data-uuid="5b32c98606924406b57f7efe467eb184">“Remember the <b><i>Maine</i></b>!”</h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="82618ff748ea471abbc54786b330f467">Images are often used as propaganda by the media to evoke emotions in order to gain the public’s attention or its support for an issue. In this case, images such as this one of the sinking of the USS <i>Maine</i>&#160;were printed by newspapers to spur support for going to war against Spain.</p>
                </div>
